  "prompt": "What is the maximum number of tabs open in Google or Computer?",
  "response": "The maximum number of tabs you can open in Google Chrome or on a computer in general isn't strictly defined by a specific number but rather by the available system resources such as RAM, CPU, and browser limitations. Here's a breakdown:\n\n### **Google Chrome:**\n1. **System Resource Limits:** Chrome allocates memory and CPU resources for each tab. The more tabs you open, the more resources are consumed. Eventually, your system will run out of available RAM or processing power, causing Chrome to slow down or crash.\n2. **Practical Limit:** On a modern computer with 8\u201316 GB of RAM, you might be able to open 50\u2013100 tabs before performance degrades significantly. On systems with more memory (e.g., 32 GB or higher), you could theoretically open hundreds of tabs, though managing them becomes impractical.\n3. **Browser Crashes:** If Chrome detects that your system is running out of memory, it may automatically close tabs or crash to prevent further issues.\n\n### **Other Browsers:**\nOther browsers like Firefox, Edge, or Safari have similar limitations based on system resources, though their memory management and efficiency may vary.\n\n### **Operating System Limits:**\nYour operating system (e.g., Windows, macOS, Linux) also plays a role. If the OS runs out of resources, it may terminate processes or freeze.\n\n### **Tips:**\n- Use **tab management extensions** (e.g., OneTab, Tab Wrangler) to reduce memory usage.\n- Close unused tabs to free up resources.\n- Upgrade your computer's RAM if you frequently work with many tabs.\n\nIn summary, there\u2019s no hard limit, but the practical maximum depends on your computer\u2019s hardware and how resource-intensive the tabs are.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
